WEBVTT

00:44.879 --> 00:48.380
[eerie organ music]

00:59.927 --> 01:06.465
[footsteps, lockers clanging]

01:16.444 --> 01:18.477
[lock dial clicking]

01:35.563 --> 01:39.465
[crickets chirping]
[flagpole clanging]

01:42.970 --> 01:45.804
[applause]

01:45.806 --> 01:47.072
LUCE:
So even though

01:47.074 --> 01:48.907
it appears as if
an evening like this

01:48.909 --> 01:51.276
is meant to honor us
for our academic achievements,

01:51.278 --> 01:54.079
I instead ask
my fellow classmates

01:54.081 --> 01:56.281
to honor the generals
that lead us.

01:56.283 --> 01:58.717
Without our parents
and our teachers,

01:58.719 --> 02:00.919
we would be troops
unprepared for the battles

02:00.921 --> 02:02.821
that lay ahead of us.

02:03.824 --> 02:05.991
We know the road won't be easy.

02:07.394 --> 02:09.828
But with your love
and your faith,

02:09.830 --> 02:11.697
we can be certain
we'll find a way.

02:13.167 --> 02:15.334
So I hope it's not going
too far out of line

02:15.336 --> 02:17.236
to ask my classmates to rise...

02:18.806 --> 02:23.142
and to take this opportunity
to thank you...

02:23.144 --> 02:25.444
our teachers...

02:25.446 --> 02:27.146
and our parents...

02:27.148 --> 02:30.516
for helping us become
who we're meant to be.

02:30.518 --> 02:36.989
[applause]

02:42.863 --> 02:45.464
I hope you enjoyed that
because tomorrow

02:45.466 --> 02:47.199
we'll be back
to driving you crazy.

02:47.201 --> 02:49.568
[laughter]

02:50.471 --> 02:51.937
It was incredible.

02:51.939 --> 02:54.139
Here's my question:
How do we clone this guy?

02:54.141 --> 02:56.175
[laughter]
How do we clone him?

02:56.177 --> 02:57.276
Great job.

02:57.278 --> 02:59.011
Thank you.
WOMAN: Excuse me.

02:59.013 --> 03:01.046
Mr. and Mr. Edgar?
LUCE: Ms. Wilson!

03:01.048 --> 03:02.514
Guys, this is Ms. Wilson,

03:02.516 --> 03:04.183
my history
and government teacher.

03:04.185 --> 03:05.551
A pleasure.

03:05.553 --> 03:07.052
We've heard
so much about you.

03:07.054 --> 03:08.954
Have you?
Well, your class.

03:08.956 --> 03:10.822
Luce can't stop
talking about it.

03:10.824 --> 03:12.457
Is that so?

03:12.459 --> 03:15.060
Ms. Wilson's tough,
but still one of my favorites.

03:15.062 --> 03:16.228
Did you like my speech?

03:16.230 --> 03:17.362
I did.

03:17.364 --> 03:18.830
Ms. Wilson's
always saying

03:18.832 --> 03:20.899
we should speak our minds
no matter the cost.

03:20.901 --> 03:22.801
Amen to that.

03:22.803 --> 03:24.836
Well, it's great
to finally meet you.

03:24.838 --> 03:26.972
You too.

03:26.974 --> 03:29.208
Luce is, uh, one of our best.

03:29.210 --> 03:31.677
He's an important
example to the school.

03:31.679 --> 03:32.844
We're very
proud of him.

03:32.846 --> 03:34.346
You should be.

03:34.348 --> 03:35.314
[Amy chuckles]

03:37.151 --> 03:39.084
Excuse me. Dan...

03:40.888 --> 03:42.821
LUCE:
I don't want
to give another one.

03:42.823 --> 03:45.224
Why? It makes sense
they asked you.

03:45.226 --> 03:46.558
You did
a great job.

03:46.560 --> 03:48.427
I literally just
gave a speech.

03:48.429 --> 03:50.329
The more public
speaking you do,

03:50.331 --> 03:51.964
the better it'll look
for college.

03:53.234 --> 03:54.833
You told them you'd do it,
right?

03:56.503 --> 03:58.103
What do you think?

03:58.105 --> 03:59.171
[Amy chuckles]

04:00.374 --> 04:02.107
So Ms. Wilson seems nice.

04:03.177 --> 04:05.010
Stern...

04:05.012 --> 04:07.012
Don't you mean a bitch?
Peter!

04:07.014 --> 04:09.948
When people say stern, they
mean bitch. You meant bitch.

04:09.950 --> 04:11.850
You didn't want to say bitch
No, I said stern.

04:11.852 --> 04:14.219
because you didn't want
to be politically incorrect

04:14.221 --> 04:15.887
but you meant bitch.
No.

04:15.889 --> 04:17.789
I know what stern
means, thank you.

04:17.791 --> 04:19.057
She is a bitch though.

04:19.059 --> 04:20.425
AMY:
Can we not denigrate a woman

04:20.427 --> 04:22.427
who probably had
to assume characteristics

04:22.429 --> 04:24.396
[snores]
[laughing] in order to attain

04:24.398 --> 04:27.132
a leadership role?

04:27.134 --> 04:29.801
Anyway, I thought you said
it was your favorite class.

04:29.803 --> 04:32.537
I like the subject.
He liked the subject.

04:32.539 --> 04:35.307
In spite of
the bitch thing.

04:35.309 --> 04:38.644
Okay, it's fine to
criticize powerful women.

04:38.646 --> 04:41.813
Just don't use
the sexist language.

04:41.815 --> 04:43.715
Strung together copy.

04:45.085 --> 04:47.552
PETER: Oh! Nice!
[Amy clicks tongue]

04:47.554 --> 04:50.055
[Luce laughs]

04:53.594 --> 04:56.628
[pop music blaring
from headphones]

04:59.967 --> 05:01.900
[keyboard clacking]

05:02.970 --> 05:04.136
[knocking at door]

05:08.075 --> 05:10.242
You should make it
personal.

05:10.244 --> 05:11.677
What?

05:11.679 --> 05:13.278
The next speech
they want you to give,

05:13.280 --> 05:14.479
make it about you.

05:16.250 --> 05:17.683
Okay. [chuckles]

05:19.253 --> 05:20.485
And listen...

05:22.690 --> 05:24.756
You're a really good
public speaker

05:24.758 --> 05:27.192
and you're an
excellent debater.

05:27.194 --> 05:28.994
But you have
your own story to tell

05:28.996 --> 05:30.495
and I think
you should tell it.

05:30.497 --> 05:32.864
It gives people
something to grab onto.

05:34.668 --> 05:36.335
Am I overstepping?

05:37.838 --> 05:39.604
It's good advice.
[chuckles]

05:40.474 --> 05:41.773
Just want to be helpful.

05:41.775 --> 05:42.741
You are.

05:44.945 --> 05:46.611
I'm going to get
back to work now.

05:48.649 --> 05:49.681
Okay.

05:52.486 --> 05:53.952
[both chuckle awkwardly]

05:55.789 --> 05:57.556
Sorry for interrupting.

05:58.726 --> 06:03.729
[indistinct conversations]

06:03.731 --> 06:05.897
[school bell rings]

06:12.005 --> 06:13.338
[sighs]
ORLICKI: Whoa!

06:13.340 --> 06:14.973
You're gonna lose
a limb like that.

06:14.975 --> 06:16.641
See my trig textbook?
I stashed it here yesterday.

06:16.643 --> 06:18.543
No, it's not here, Orlicki.

06:18.545 --> 06:19.911
Fuck me.
You do realize

06:19.913 --> 06:21.580
everyone gets their
own locker, right?

06:21.582 --> 06:23.148
Mine's on the other
side of the building,

06:23.150 --> 06:26.585
makes me late all the time.
Ah, shit! Orlicki!

06:26.587 --> 06:29.721
Heard our boy here got asked to
give another speech last night?

06:29.723 --> 06:31.490
Seriously?
Oh, motherfucking

06:31.492 --> 06:33.392
Nelson Mandela over here!

06:33.394 --> 06:35.026
I don't get why
I never get asked.

06:35.028 --> 06:36.528
'cause you're a C+ student.

06:36.530 --> 06:38.830
The entire speech would be
about porn and blunts.

06:38.832 --> 06:40.399
ORLICKI: Ah! Fair enough.

06:40.401 --> 06:42.234
BOTH: [in rhythm]
Ah! Ah! Ah!

06:42.236 --> 06:44.503
Oh, shit! Check it out!

06:44.505 --> 06:45.771
Hey, yo, ladies!

06:45.773 --> 06:48.340
Stephanie Kim, what's good?
Let's go.

06:49.576 --> 06:51.343
Why you staring at Luce,
Stephanie?

06:51.345 --> 06:52.544
I'm talking to you.

06:52.546 --> 06:54.212
Not everyone likes
your big mouth.

06:54.214 --> 06:55.447
Your mama does.

06:55.449 --> 06:56.848
She loves my big mouth.

06:56.850 --> 06:58.550
Loves it all
over that pussy!

06:58.552 --> 07:00.852
Man, you're so gross!

07:00.854 --> 07:02.554
Sorry, bro.

07:02.556 --> 07:04.589
Hey yo, I'll see you
all at practice.

07:04.591 --> 07:07.292
[indistinct voice from video]

07:07.294 --> 07:09.461
FEMALE STUDENT:
A law is a law.

07:09.463 --> 07:11.696
Pole-tests used to be law.

07:11.698 --> 07:13.732
So was segregation.
Red lining.

07:13.734 --> 07:15.467
FEMALE STUDENT:
That's not the same.

07:15.469 --> 07:17.035
Explain why.

07:17.037 --> 07:18.470
FEMALE STUDENT:
It's just not.

07:18.472 --> 07:20.071
Things were
different back then.

07:20.073 --> 07:21.373
Different how?

07:21.375 --> 07:23.542
Well, like that was
a different time.

07:23.544 --> 07:24.943
Social norms were different.

07:24.945 --> 07:26.478
People's expectations,

07:26.480 --> 07:27.779
their attitudes...

07:34.455 --> 07:36.455
MS. WILSON:
Is this not important to you?

07:38.659 --> 07:39.658
Well?

07:40.494 --> 07:41.827
It is.

07:41.829 --> 07:43.962
You might want
to speak more clearly.

07:43.964 --> 07:45.063
I can't hear you.

07:46.834 --> 07:48.467
It is.

07:48.469 --> 07:51.736
Keep in mind,
that for her,

07:51.738 --> 07:53.772
this knowledge is
incidental but for you

07:53.774 --> 07:55.407
it can be
life or death.

07:55.409 --> 07:58.243
So you might want
to treat this material

07:58.245 --> 08:01.179
with the seriousness
it deserves, Mr. Meeks.

08:09.790 --> 08:13.625
Which reminds me,
I'm almost done

08:13.627 --> 08:15.694
grading your assignments.
I apologize,

08:15.696 --> 08:17.796
it's taking me a little
longer than usual but,

08:17.798 --> 08:19.130
you'll have them
back soon.

08:19.132 --> 08:21.500
[¶¶¶]

08:21.502 --> 08:23.969
All right...
[school bell rings]

08:23.971 --> 08:25.337
LUCE: Yo, Deshaun...

08:27.474 --> 08:29.040
Yo, Deshaun!

08:40.120 --> 08:42.687
Let's have a look in here.
Okay...

08:44.391 --> 08:46.825
Let's see...
He-he! That feels funny!

08:46.827 --> 08:48.226
Oh yeah?

08:48.228 --> 08:49.494
What about that?
[laughs]

08:49.496 --> 08:51.696
Does that feel funny?
[laughs]

08:51.698 --> 08:53.665
Hey.

08:53.667 --> 08:56.334
How do you feel about
a weekend trip to Cornell?

08:56.336 --> 08:58.036
PETER: <i> This weekend? </i>
Yeah.

08:58.038 --> 09:01.139
Maggie's sister said she'd make
a call and get Luce some

09:01.141 --> 09:03.074
<i> one-on-one time</i>
<i> with the professor.</i>

09:03.076 --> 09:07.178
This weekend we have
the sip-and-see.

09:07.180 --> 09:09.514
Oh my God!
PETER: <i> If you don't want to go,</i>

09:09.516 --> 09:11.216
<i> you should have said, right?</i>

09:11.218 --> 09:14.252
Yeah, well, it's not that
I don't want to go. I mean,

09:14.254 --> 09:16.988
<i> I don't want to go, but-- </i>
No, you just hate babies.

09:16.990 --> 09:18.523
AMY:
<i> I do not hate babies.</i>

09:18.525 --> 09:20.559
PETER:
I mean, I love babies!

09:20.561 --> 09:21.927
But you hate babies.

09:21.929 --> 09:24.930
Well, I'm just shocked
you're prioritizing

09:24.932 --> 09:28.033
your ex's sip-and-see over
your son's college education,

09:28.035 --> 09:29.434
but hey, that's just me.

09:29.436 --> 09:31.570
PETER:
<i>Okay. Punchline and point made.</i>

09:31.572 --> 09:33.104
[laughs]

09:33.106 --> 09:35.206
Okay, fine.
You're in charge of picking up

09:35.208 --> 09:37.876
whatever someone brings
to a sip-and-see.

09:37.878 --> 09:39.945
Got it. Okay,
see you at home.

09:39.947 --> 09:40.946
AMY:
<i> See ya.</i>

09:42.916 --> 09:46.518
[phone ringing]

09:46.520 --> 09:47.485
Hello?

09:49.256 --> 09:50.355
Yes, this is Amy.

09:52.459 --> 09:53.458
MAN:
On your mark...

09:54.561 --> 09:55.560
Set...

09:55.562 --> 09:56.561
Go!
[gunshot]

09:56.563 --> 09:59.097
[hip hop beat]

09:59.099 --> 10:01.833
[cheering]

10:13.280 --> 10:15.647
[cheerleaders shout in rhythm]

10:18.151 --> 10:20.385
[panting]

10:26.760 --> 10:28.026
Yo!

10:30.964 --> 10:33.031
Mrs. Edgar.
Hi.

10:34.468 --> 10:36.601
I appreciate you coming
back down here.

10:36.603 --> 10:39.070
Well, you have to make time
for what's important.

10:39.072 --> 10:40.338
Ain't that
the truth.

10:40.340 --> 10:43.274
Kids are lucky to have you.
Thank you.

10:43.276 --> 10:46.144
Luce too.
Oh, we're lucky to have him.

10:46.146 --> 10:48.913
We care a great deal
about his success.

10:48.915 --> 10:51.616
Peter and I too.
Of course.

10:51.618 --> 10:54.419
And I know
context matters.

10:54.421 --> 10:55.553
Please, sit.

10:56.923 --> 10:59.357
Given Luce's
background,

10:59.359 --> 11:02.961
you and Peter must have faced
quite a few challenges.

11:02.963 --> 11:04.963
the language barrier,
the culture shock.

11:04.965 --> 11:06.264
He's a resilient kid.

11:06.266 --> 11:08.133
He is.
But it's also

11:08.135 --> 11:09.601
a testament to
your parenting.

11:09.603 --> 11:11.703
Well, thank you.

11:11.705 --> 11:13.004
We had a lot of support,

11:13.006 --> 11:15.440
especially in the
early days. I mean,

11:15.442 --> 11:17.308
you don't pull a kid
out of a war zone

11:17.310 --> 11:19.611
and have him turn out like
Luce without a lot of help.

11:19.613 --> 11:21.146
I bet.

11:21.148 --> 11:23.214
Which is why this
is so difficult.

11:24.151 --> 11:25.116
Difficult?

11:29.623 --> 11:32.691
Last week, the class
was given an assignment

11:32.693 --> 11:35.694
to write in the voice
of an historical figure.

11:35.696 --> 11:39.798
Some students picked FDR at the
start of the Great Depression

11:39.800 --> 11:41.066
or even Fidel Castro

11:41.068 --> 11:43.134
at the Bay of Pigs.

11:43.136 --> 11:46.638
The goal was to get them
to think outside of the box.

11:46.640 --> 11:49.307
Want to make sure you understand
where I'm coming from.

11:51.578 --> 11:52.777
Please.

11:56.383 --> 11:58.149
[¶¶¶]

11:58.151 --> 12:03.121
[shower water running]
[indistinct voices]

12:15.335 --> 12:17.001
[exhales]

12:21.508 --> 12:24.509
Who is this Frantz Fanon?

12:24.511 --> 12:27.579
He was a pan-African
revolutionary.

12:27.581 --> 12:31.583
He argued that violence was
a necessary cleansing force,

12:31.585 --> 12:33.384
that it was needed to
free colonized people

12:33.386 --> 12:34.586
from their rulers.

12:34.588 --> 12:36.955
You-you teach this?
I don't.

12:37.891 --> 12:39.190
Look,

12:39.192 --> 12:41.860
I won't pretend
to know what it's like

12:41.862 --> 12:44.763
for Luce to confront
certain aspects of who he is

12:44.765 --> 12:47.098
and it's not
within my purview

12:47.100 --> 12:50.535
to say what a boy who spent
his first 10 years in...

12:50.537 --> 12:51.503
Eritrea.

12:52.439 --> 12:53.705
Right.

12:53.707 --> 12:55.206
What that might
have been like,

12:55.208 --> 12:57.742
what kind of adjustments
he must have made

12:57.744 --> 12:58.943
in order to fit in here.

12:58.945 --> 13:00.812
And I don't know

13:00.814 --> 13:03.414
the details of his treatment--
I'm sure you've heard

13:03.416 --> 13:05.150
he went through
years of recovery

13:05.152 --> 13:07.886
and he showed no signs of--
I-I didn't mean to imply--

13:07.888 --> 13:09.888
I just want to be clear
that whatever

13:09.890 --> 13:13.224
violence he both suffered and
inflicted during that time

13:13.226 --> 13:15.827
was dealt with,
it's been processed.

13:15.829 --> 13:17.228
Of course.

13:17.230 --> 13:20.165
But with the climate
around school security

13:20.167 --> 13:23.101
the way it is right now,
you can understand my concern.

13:23.103 --> 13:24.435
Yes.

13:24.437 --> 13:25.737
Which is why I felt

13:25.739 --> 13:27.739
I needed to search
his locker.

13:27.741 --> 13:29.741
I'm sorry?
Amy...

13:29.743 --> 13:31.109
He wrote a paper.

13:31.111 --> 13:33.144
A paper in which
he describes

13:33.146 --> 13:35.647
his belief that the solution
to a political problem

13:35.649 --> 13:37.749
is to gun down those
with whom you disagree.

13:37.751 --> 13:39.584
Right. But he was
assuming a character.

13:39.586 --> 13:41.986
The assignment called
for this and you--

13:45.926 --> 13:47.692
I found this in his locker.

13:51.665 --> 13:52.797
No.
Amy.

13:52.799 --> 13:53.798
No, I'm sorry.

13:53.800 --> 13:56.100
I respect my son's privacy.

13:56.102 --> 13:58.269
Now, he wrote a paper
that scared you. Fine.

13:58.271 --> 13:59.470
That's between
you and him.

13:59.472 --> 14:01.206
But I won't,
I will not violate

14:01.208 --> 14:03.341
his right to the privacy
he's owed.

14:03.343 --> 14:05.276
They're fireworks.

14:05.278 --> 14:07.779
Illegal and very dangerous
fireworks.

14:07.781 --> 14:10.014
They could put a hole
in the wall, let alone--

14:10.016 --> 14:11.983
Where are you going with this?

14:11.985 --> 14:14.485
Right now I'm the only one
who knows about them,

14:14.487 --> 14:16.888
but what if someone else
were to find them?

14:16.890 --> 14:19.958
If someone who didn't know
Luce the way you and I do

14:19.960 --> 14:22.994
were to stumble on this within
the context of his background

14:22.996 --> 14:24.596
having written this...

14:25.498 --> 14:26.531
Take them.

14:27.300 --> 14:28.266
Talk to him.

14:30.337 --> 14:33.204
Who he is is too important
to this school

14:33.206 --> 14:34.672
for him to fuck it up.

14:34.674 --> 14:36.941
He can't fuck it up.

14:38.478 --> 14:40.078
Talk to him, please.

14:45.652 --> 14:46.718
I will.

14:48.855 --> 14:50.822
ORLICKI:
You're the one who keeps
talking about Stephanie.

14:50.824 --> 14:52.323
COREY: I'm not!
The fuck is wrong with you?

14:52.325 --> 14:54.225
Shut it!
Get off me!

14:54.227 --> 14:56.327
COREY:
You should have kept
your mouth shut, little shit.

14:56.329 --> 14:57.495
ORLICKI:
I told you!

14:57.497 --> 14:58.997
Yo, what the hell! Come on!

14:58.999 --> 15:00.765
He told everybody!
Fuck you!

15:00.767 --> 15:04.168
[indistinct shouting]

15:04.170 --> 15:05.904
If this gets out,
it's on your two.

15:05.906 --> 15:07.338
Both of you!
COACH: Yo!

15:09.109 --> 15:11.743
Everything okay?
Everything's fine, coach.

15:14.714 --> 15:16.881
Luce, my office.

15:16.883 --> 15:18.116
Sure thing.

15:25.292 --> 15:26.758
AMY:
You read the whole thing?

15:26.760 --> 15:28.126
Yeah.

15:28.128 --> 15:30.595
Okay, yeah, kids get
taken with ideas.

15:30.597 --> 15:31.930
Look, he probably stumbled

15:31.932 --> 15:33.865
across Frantz Fanon
on the internet

15:33.867 --> 15:35.466
and went overboard.

15:35.468 --> 15:37.902
I read the Communist Manifesto
when I was an undergrad

15:37.904 --> 15:40.038
and called people
comrade for a month.

15:40.040 --> 15:42.874
Yeah, well, I think he's
a little too smart for that.

15:42.876 --> 15:45.443
Not too smart to have
explosives in his locker.

15:45.445 --> 15:47.645
They're fireworks.
Illegal fireworks

15:47.647 --> 15:49.614
Still--
that have explosive capacity,

15:49.616 --> 15:51.749
I Googled this,
of a shotgun blast.

15:51.751 --> 15:52.750
They're fireworks.

15:52.752 --> 15:54.953
It's not shocking.

15:54.955 --> 15:56.688
That is shocking.

15:58.091 --> 16:00.258
Okay, so what?

16:00.260 --> 16:02.994
So what?
What? What, our...

16:04.331 --> 16:07.031
teenage soon-to-be
valedictorian son is,

16:07.968 --> 16:09.734
secretly a radical?
No.

16:09.736 --> 16:10.802
A terrorist?
No.

16:10.804 --> 16:12.303
No. Of course not.
What then?

16:12.305 --> 16:14.472
I don't know. It's just
something's going on

16:14.474 --> 16:16.074
and I want to be
in front of it.

16:16.076 --> 16:18.409
[keys jangling]
Oh shit.

16:18.411 --> 16:19.877
PETER:
Amy, what the fuck?

16:21.514 --> 16:22.747
Hey!
Hey.

16:22.749 --> 16:23.982
How was school?

16:29.089 --> 16:30.221
What's going on?

16:31.157 --> 16:32.357
Nothing.

16:32.359 --> 16:34.325
How was school?
How was practice?

16:34.327 --> 16:35.560
[indistinct]

16:36.663 --> 16:37.662
Psy.

16:39.366 --> 16:41.866
Have you eaten?
Not yet.

16:41.868 --> 16:44.669
Oh good, because
your dad picked up curry.

16:44.671 --> 16:45.670
Sweet!

16:46.840 --> 16:47.839
[coughs]

16:50.710 --> 16:52.877
[slight chuckles]

16:52.879 --> 16:55.713
Okay, put your stuff down
so we can eat.

16:55.715 --> 16:58.016
Cool.
Great.

16:58.018 --> 16:59.884
Don't start without me.
We won't.

17:01.287 --> 17:02.687
Hey...

17:02.689 --> 17:04.821
What was that?
I don't want him to know

17:04.824 --> 17:06.891
we've gone through his things.
We didn't.

17:06.893 --> 17:09.660
Or make it seem we went behind
his back to his teachers.

17:09.662 --> 17:11.128
Amy...
Come on, Pete.

17:11.131 --> 17:13.131
How many years did it take us
to get him here?

17:13.133 --> 17:15.465
How many nights did I crawl
underneath that bed

17:15.468 --> 17:17.502
because he was too scared
to sleep in it?

17:17.503 --> 17:19.137
What we've built.
That trust.

17:19.138 --> 17:21.439
I won't risk it.
I won't.

17:22.509 --> 17:25.710
[¶¶¶]

17:25.712 --> 17:27.944
[rag squeaks on mirror]

17:35.989 --> 17:37.655
MS. WILSON:
I got everything ready.

17:39.359 --> 17:41.759
Yes, I'll be by to talk
with the doctors tomorrow

17:41.761 --> 17:42.827
and we'll be all set.

17:44.197 --> 17:45.730
Rose...

17:45.732 --> 17:47.398
Rose, I told you already, okay?

17:49.269 --> 17:51.769
Okay. I'll see you soon.

17:52.505 --> 17:53.771
I love you too.

18:05.085 --> 18:07.251
[sprinkler whirring outside]

18:11.124 --> 18:12.523
[cutlery clinks]

18:14.961 --> 18:16.027
[sighs]

18:17.363 --> 18:18.930
Okay, so who told you?

18:18.932 --> 18:22.200
Told us what?
You clearly know.

18:22.202 --> 18:23.468
What do we know?

18:23.470 --> 18:25.870
LUCE:
You don't-- You don't know?

18:25.872 --> 18:29.707
What is it that you think
we do or do not know, honey?

18:30.276 --> 18:31.442
Um...

18:33.480 --> 18:35.279
Coach Reeves
offered me Captain.

18:35.281 --> 18:36.314
Wow!
Whoa.

18:36.316 --> 18:38.416
Oh my God!
That's amazing!

18:38.418 --> 18:39.784
Yeah! It's dope.

18:39.786 --> 18:41.285
Says I'll be
good example

18:41.287 --> 18:43.588
for certain teammates.
But between track

18:43.590 --> 18:46.257
and debate prep, plus the extra
shit Wilson has us doing...

18:46.259 --> 18:47.492
What, how do you mean?

18:47.494 --> 18:49.827
Nothing. It's just...

18:51.064 --> 18:52.697
You really don't like her,
do you?

18:53.566 --> 18:54.732
It's complicated.

18:55.802 --> 18:57.034
Try me.

18:58.571 --> 19:00.805
Okay. You remember
Stephanie Kim, right?

19:02.809 --> 19:04.509
Sort of...
Not a clue.

19:04.511 --> 19:06.344
She came over one time last...

19:06.346 --> 19:08.412
AMY: Go on.
Anyway.

19:08.414 --> 19:10.348
There were rumors
going around about her

19:10.350 --> 19:11.983
after this party
a few weeks ago.

19:11.985 --> 19:14.352
What kind of rumors?
Oh, people were drinking

19:14.354 --> 19:16.787
and no one really knows
what happened, but, um...

19:16.789 --> 19:18.356
Stephanie got
kind of messed up.

19:18.358 --> 19:19.857
Something happened
with some guys.

19:19.859 --> 19:21.659
Then Wilson got involved

19:21.661 --> 19:23.794
and no one really
could prove anything

19:23.796 --> 19:26.631
but she kept using Stephanie
as like an example.

19:26.633 --> 19:28.166
turning her
into a victim.

19:28.168 --> 19:30.001
How?
Well,

19:30.003 --> 19:33.204
we'll be talking about women
in Middle East or something

19:33.206 --> 19:35.706
and she singles her out,
says some shit like,

19:35.708 --> 19:38.309
"We all know firsthand
how important it is for women

19:38.311 --> 19:40.978
to have the courage
to stand up, to fight."

19:40.980 --> 19:42.547
AMY: I don't understand.

19:42.549 --> 19:44.348
It's not exactly
singling her out.

19:44.350 --> 19:45.850
It's how she says it.

19:45.852 --> 19:47.451
Like everyone's
a symbol to her.

19:47.453 --> 19:49.720
Stephanie, Deshaun,
we all exist

19:49.722 --> 19:52.190
to confirm the world
is the way she sees it.

19:52.192 --> 19:53.991
AMY:
So does she do that
kind of thing with you?

19:53.993 --> 19:55.826
[scoffs]
Are you kidding?

19:55.828 --> 19:57.228
I'm a fucking
poster boy.

19:57.230 --> 19:59.730
Black kid who overcame
his tragic past,

19:59.732 --> 20:01.933
the example why America
works. It's bullshit.

20:03.169 --> 20:05.203
So you don't like her
labeling you?

20:05.205 --> 20:07.305
I don't like tokenism.

20:07.307 --> 20:09.640
What's the difference
between punishing someone

20:09.642 --> 20:12.577
for being a stereotype and
rewarding them if they're not?

20:12.579 --> 20:14.645
One of the two
comes with benefits.

20:14.647 --> 20:16.147
What you'd call a benefit,

20:16.149 --> 20:17.748
I'd call a responsibility
I didn't ask for.

20:17.750 --> 20:20.451
Okay, what about responsibility
to tell the truth?

20:21.521 --> 20:22.520
What?
Peter...

20:22.522 --> 20:23.754
So, one of the

20:23.756 --> 20:25.756
benefits you get
is benefit of the doubt.

20:25.758 --> 20:27.992
A chance to explain yourself.
Explain myself?

20:27.994 --> 20:29.327
AMY: Enough.
Whereas another student

20:29.329 --> 20:30.828
might not. So...

20:32.599 --> 20:34.498
You have anything
you want to tell us?

20:34.500 --> 20:36.300
AMY: Peter, stop.
About what?

20:40.373 --> 20:41.572
Ask your mom.

20:46.446 --> 20:47.845
Finish your food.

20:59.959 --> 21:01.325
[sighs]

21:14.874 --> 21:17.608
[eerie, airy music]

21:36.462 --> 21:39.196
[inaudible]

21:46.239 --> 21:49.573
[keyboard clacking]

21:57.317 --> 21:58.316
[click]

22:08.761 --> 22:09.927
[click]

22:12.098 --> 22:13.664
[birds chirping]

22:15.368 --> 22:16.367
[door opens]

22:25.144 --> 22:26.177
[car horn honks]

22:34.887 --> 22:38.022
[flagpole clanging]

22:54.040 --> 22:55.339
Knock knock.

22:55.341 --> 22:58.142
Hey!
We've been summoned.

22:58.144 --> 22:59.877
[knocking on door]

22:59.879 --> 23:01.078
Honey...

23:26.105 --> 23:27.104
[door opens]

23:30.777 --> 23:32.376
Prosecutor Edgar,

23:32.378 --> 23:34.412
take it easy on me today.
How are you all doing?

23:34.414 --> 23:36.347
Ms. Wilson, so glad
you could join us.

23:36.349 --> 23:39.083
Luce was hoping to get some
help building his next case.

23:39.085 --> 23:41.519
I figure you and Principal Dan
are the all stars.

23:41.521 --> 23:43.888
We're going to nationals
again this year, right?

23:43.890 --> 23:45.856
100 percent.
Boom!

23:45.858 --> 23:47.892
That's why this one's
my thoroughbred.

23:47.894 --> 23:49.260
Okay, let's have it.

23:49.262 --> 23:51.095
Ms. Wilson...

23:51.097 --> 23:54.265
Of course. Let's, uh,
let's hear what you got.

23:59.539 --> 24:01.705
What are you doing?
Jesus, Pete!

24:03.209 --> 24:05.109
Doesn't it make sense
just to get rid of them?

24:05.111 --> 24:06.277
They're so dangerous.

24:06.279 --> 24:07.545
We hang on to them

24:07.547 --> 24:09.280
until we get to
the bottom of this.

24:11.884 --> 24:13.217
They'll be
safe here.

24:15.121 --> 24:16.120
What?

24:16.923 --> 24:17.888
What?

24:25.731 --> 24:26.831
LUCE:
My argument

24:26.833 --> 24:29.099
is premised on
two court cases:

24:29.101 --> 24:31.469
Goss v. Lopez,
1975,

24:31.471 --> 24:34.672
and New Jersey
v. T.L.O., 1985.

24:34.674 --> 24:37.842
In Goss, an Ohio school
suspended nine students

24:37.844 --> 24:39.143
for delinquent behavior,

24:39.145 --> 24:40.845
but the Supreme Court found

24:40.847 --> 24:43.414
that depriving students of
their right to an education

24:43.416 --> 24:44.582
without
due process

24:44.584 --> 24:46.784
is a violation
of their civil rights.

24:46.786 --> 24:48.486
Ms. Wilson,
do you agree with that?

24:48.488 --> 24:50.287
I'm sorry?

24:50.289 --> 24:51.956
LUCE:
Do you agree that those kids

24:51.958 --> 24:54.525
were deprived of
their civil rights?

24:54.527 --> 24:57.695
I don't know the specifics
of the case but

24:57.697 --> 25:00.264
the principal--
Principal makes sense, right?

25:00.266 --> 25:01.632
Education is a civil right.

25:01.634 --> 25:03.033
Everyone should have
civil rights.

25:03.035 --> 25:05.135
Right.
In the second case

25:05.137 --> 25:08.806
a student is accused of smoking
in the school bathroom,

25:08.808 --> 25:10.374
but there's no proof.

25:10.376 --> 25:12.877
The charge is premised
on a teacher's suspicion.

25:12.879 --> 25:16.113
So the principal searched
her purse and found cigarettes

25:16.115 --> 25:18.115
and marijuana-related
paraphernalia.

25:18.117 --> 25:19.450
Do you agree with that?

25:19.452 --> 25:21.218
What did the court say?

25:21.220 --> 25:22.720
The court found that students

25:22.722 --> 25:25.689
have a reduced expectation
of privacy in schools.

25:26.359 --> 25:27.358
It makes sense.

25:27.360 --> 25:28.792
Does it?

25:28.794 --> 25:33.564
A school is a unique
social institution.

25:33.566 --> 25:35.666
It's populated by people
who aren't adults

25:35.668 --> 25:38.402
in the eyes of the law.
People who have to be here.

25:38.404 --> 25:40.538
Students.
Yes.

25:40.540 --> 25:41.805
Students are half people.

25:41.807 --> 25:43.173
LENA:
Luce,

25:43.175 --> 25:45.142
is there a specific
question you have

25:45.144 --> 25:47.344
that Ms. Wilson
might be able to address?

25:47.346 --> 25:48.345
Totally.

25:48.347 --> 25:50.481
Thanks Ms. Tennyson.

25:50.483 --> 25:52.383
Um, basically my question

25:52.385 --> 25:54.518
that I hope Ms. Wilson
can help me with

25:54.520 --> 25:57.555
is around this idea
of reduced expectation

25:57.557 --> 26:00.758
versus the affirmation by the
court of student civil rights.

26:00.760 --> 26:02.760
Like what are the criteria
for evaluating

26:02.762 --> 26:04.528
what's a violation
of privacy?

26:04.530 --> 26:06.263
Is privacy a civil right?

26:06.265 --> 26:07.598
LUCE:
I think so.

26:07.600 --> 26:09.466
Maybe the law isn't so sure.

26:11.938 --> 26:14.338
If I went through your desk
without you knowing,

26:14.340 --> 26:16.307
would you feel like
your privacy was violated?

26:18.578 --> 26:20.377
Yes, I would.

26:20.379 --> 26:22.279
So?

26:22.281 --> 26:24.515
Feelings aren't
a legal argument.

26:24.517 --> 26:27.451
In the New Jersey case,
the teacher assumed

26:27.453 --> 26:29.720
the girl was guilty
because of her feelings.

26:29.722 --> 26:32.690
That's called
reasonable suspicion.

26:32.692 --> 26:35.593
It's all the police need
to search your car.

26:35.595 --> 26:38.128
LUCE:
So it's about what's reasonable.

26:38.130 --> 26:40.631
That's what courts are for.

26:42.234 --> 26:45.069
Really it's just about
people though, right?

26:45.071 --> 26:47.371
Whether they conform
to what we think they are.

26:49.041 --> 26:50.207
It's not that simple.

26:51.277 --> 26:52.610
Nothing ever is.

26:55.982 --> 26:57.648
[school bell rings]

26:57.650 --> 26:59.817
Thank you so much
for your help, Ms. Wilson.

26:59.819 --> 27:01.418
This was,
this was great, right?

27:01.420 --> 27:03.587
Any time.

27:03.589 --> 27:05.823
God, that kid is
something else, isn't he?

27:07.326 --> 27:11.729
[indistinct conversations]

27:16.135 --> 27:17.401
[school bell rings]

27:17.403 --> 27:19.036
All right, people,
phones away.

27:20.673 --> 27:21.939
I see you, Sasha.

27:21.941 --> 27:23.841
And you too,
Stephanie Kim.

27:25.578 --> 27:27.578
All right.
CHEERLEADERS: It's show time!

27:27.580 --> 27:29.079
You fucked up.
And bro,

27:29.081 --> 27:31.115
you can't just go slamming
Orlicki against a locker.

27:31.117 --> 27:32.516
He's out there
telling everybody.

27:32.518 --> 27:35.119
It's nothing half the school
didn't already know.

27:35.121 --> 27:37.121
Besides, I talked
to Stephanie.

27:37.123 --> 27:38.956
You two still talk?

27:38.958 --> 27:40.658
Not really, but someone
had to resolve this

27:40.660 --> 27:42.926
before it blows up.
Is she gonna be cool?

27:42.928 --> 27:44.261
Yeah.
Is she gonna be cool?

27:44.263 --> 27:45.929
Everything's going
to be cool, man.

27:45.931 --> 27:48.766
Just squash the beef
with Orlicki, all right?

27:48.768 --> 27:51.335
Corey!
All right, man. Whatever.

27:54.473 --> 27:57.441
Yo! Deshaun's
one bold-ass nigga.

27:57.443 --> 27:59.710
COREY:
Since Wilson got him
tossed off the team,

27:59.712 --> 28:00.944
he's been messed up.

28:05.651 --> 28:08.118
I'll catch you later, man.

28:08.120 --> 28:09.420
Yo.
Yeah.

28:11.724 --> 28:14.358
[phone chimes]

28:19.498 --> 28:21.165
MS. WILSON:
We agreed on this.

28:21.167 --> 28:24.301
If you live with me,
you have to be responsible for--

28:24.303 --> 28:27.304
All I ask is if you're staying
on top of your medication.

28:28.641 --> 28:30.507
I know what the doctor
said, Rosemary.

28:30.509 --> 28:32.910
It doesn't mean
I'm comfortable with it.

28:32.912 --> 28:35.045
MS. WILSON:
Out of everyone in this family,

28:35.047 --> 28:36.513
I've been there for you
time and time again.

28:36.515 --> 28:37.514
I resent that.

28:37.516 --> 28:39.083
[knocks on door]
Hey.

28:39.085 --> 28:41.752
I gotta go, Rose.
We'll talk tonight.

28:44.356 --> 28:46.890
Everything okay?
Everything's fine.

28:46.892 --> 28:48.826
Family stuff?

28:48.828 --> 28:50.327
Personal business, yes.

28:50.329 --> 28:51.295
Gotcha.

28:52.698 --> 28:54.765
Um, thanks for your
guidance this morning.

28:54.767 --> 28:56.667
It really helped
make my case.

28:56.669 --> 28:58.569
I'm glad.

28:58.571 --> 29:00.237
You wanted to see me?

29:00.239 --> 29:02.873
I wanted to talk to you about
your assignment, Luce.

29:02.875 --> 29:04.374
What about it?

29:04.376 --> 29:06.510
I assumed you spoke
to your mother...

29:06.512 --> 29:09.680
I haven't gotten it back yet.
How could I talk my mom of it?

29:11.383 --> 29:14.084
Well, I'll just say, uh...

29:14.086 --> 29:15.953
After reading it,
I have some concerns

29:15.955 --> 29:17.688
for some of
the arguments you made.

29:17.690 --> 29:19.356
Well they aren't mine.

29:19.358 --> 29:20.591
Excuse me?

29:20.593 --> 29:22.459
The arguments,
they're Frantz Fanon's.

29:22.461 --> 29:24.228
I realize that.

29:24.230 --> 29:25.929
The assignment was
to write in his voice.

29:25.931 --> 29:27.798
You really think
I believe that stuff?

29:27.800 --> 29:30.434
Well, I don't know.

29:30.436 --> 29:33.437
If I didn't know you, Luce,
it would be reasonable for me

29:33.439 --> 29:35.305
to read that assignment
and conclude--

29:35.307 --> 29:36.440
But you do know me.

29:39.278 --> 29:41.245
Look, um,

29:41.247 --> 29:43.247
I'm sorry if I scared you.

29:43.249 --> 29:45.549
I just wanted to do
a good job.

29:45.551 --> 29:47.651
You did do a good job.

29:47.653 --> 29:49.219
I mean, I get it.

29:49.221 --> 29:50.988
Get what?
Well, I get

29:50.990 --> 29:53.991
how someone who learned how to
shoot a gun before driving a car

29:53.993 --> 29:55.392
writing something like that

29:55.394 --> 29:57.161
might make someone
freaked out.

29:58.798 --> 30:01.398
I just hope you know me
better than that, Ms. Wilson.

30:03.002 --> 30:05.469
I like to think
that I do, Luce.

30:07.640 --> 30:09.840
Anything else you wanted
to talk to me about?

30:10.409 --> 30:11.809
No.

30:11.811 --> 30:13.510
Tell your mom
I'd like her to call me.

30:14.013 --> 30:15.012
Why?

30:16.515 --> 30:18.182
Because I want
to speak with her.

30:19.018 --> 30:20.951
What about? I mean,

30:20.953 --> 30:24.087
I guess it's about me unless you
guys are friends or something.

30:24.089 --> 30:25.622
Please have her
call me, Luce.

30:25.624 --> 30:27.157
Thank you for
stopping in.

30:27.159 --> 30:28.325
Of course.

30:33.632 --> 30:34.898
Hey, Ms. Wilson...

30:36.035 --> 30:37.634
What's your favorite holiday?

30:37.636 --> 30:41.171
Excuse me?
What's your favorite holiday?

30:41.173 --> 30:43.473
I don't know.
Christmas maybe.

30:43.475 --> 30:44.875
Mine is Independence Day.

30:44.877 --> 30:46.677
[¶¶¶]

30:46.679 --> 30:48.445
Before I came here,

30:48.447 --> 30:50.848
I didn't know
a single holiday and

30:50.850 --> 30:54.618
I remember my mom trying
to explain what they were.

30:54.620 --> 30:57.120
It's a hard concept to grasp
if you've never of it,

30:57.122 --> 30:58.722
but,

30:58.724 --> 31:01.158
once I learned them all,
my favorite, hands down,

31:01.160 --> 31:03.861
has always been
Independence Day.

31:03.863 --> 31:04.862
Why is that?

31:04.864 --> 31:06.730
I like what it represents.

31:08.234 --> 31:10.167
Freedom,

31:10.169 --> 31:11.201
strength,

31:12.671 --> 31:13.871
individuality.

31:15.541 --> 31:19.042
Also I love the fireworks.
The lights.

31:19.044 --> 31:20.244
Poof!

31:22.014 --> 31:25.148
Luce, I'd like to remind you
that you're still a student here

31:25.150 --> 31:27.317
and I am your teacher.

31:27.319 --> 31:31.521
And regardless of what you may
view as some sort of injustice

31:31.523 --> 31:33.523
What are you talking about?
...or unfair,

31:33.525 --> 31:36.260
just remember how things
are organized around here.

31:38.097 --> 31:40.130
Totally.
I'll see you around.

31:51.377 --> 31:54.211
The financials from Cusack.
Thanks, Beth.

31:54.213 --> 31:56.046
Quarter end payments
went out, right?

31:56.048 --> 31:59.950
Yes.
[cell phone vibrating]

32:02.855 --> 32:03.854
Yeah?

32:06.225 --> 32:08.825
Ms. Wilson.
How are you?

32:13.866 --> 32:15.632
Why is she calling you?

32:15.634 --> 32:18.201
Well, last I checked
I'm one of two parents.

32:18.203 --> 32:20.203
Yeah, but she was
communicating with me

32:20.205 --> 32:21.705
and now she's calling you?

32:21.707 --> 32:24.374
Well, we're both available
to talk about our son.

32:24.376 --> 32:28.045
This woman has some kind
of vendetta against Luce.

32:28.047 --> 32:29.479
Vendetta? Really?
Yeah.

32:29.481 --> 32:31.882
She has some <i> thing </i>
with him and now,

32:31.884 --> 32:33.917
now she's trying to
divide and conquer.

32:33.919 --> 32:35.385
Nice word choice.

32:35.387 --> 32:36.920
What she did
with Stephanie Kim

32:36.922 --> 32:38.989
and what she's trying
to do now with Luce,

32:38.991 --> 32:41.825
